#3. Find how many songs that have danceability higher than the median dancebility, energy lower than the median energy, loudness lower than the median loudness, speechiness higher than the medain speechiness, and the popularity is 1.

library(dplyr)
median_danceability <- median(songs$danceability)
median_energy <- median(songs$energy)
median_loudness <- median(songs$loudness)
median_speechiness <- median(songs$speechiness)
num_songs_filtered <- songs %>%
  filter(danceability > median_danceability,
         energy < median_energy,
         loudness < median_loudness,
         speechiness > median_speechiness,
         popularity == 1) %>%
  nrow()
print(num_songs_filtered)
## [1] 288

#5. Change the data type of popularity to a factor in the data frame songs and create a boxplot of the distribution of duration_ms by popularity. Discuss the distribution of durations_ms by popularity.

When looking at the distribution of the durations_ms by popularity one may notice there are numerous outliers within the data. With this one might take into the consider the effect how accurate the data may be. Along with this one may also notice lots of similarities in popularity’s medians as they are all very similar, and have similar IQR’s.

library(ggplot2)
songs <- songs %>%
  mutate(popularity = as.factor(popularity))
ggplot(songs, aes(x = popularity, y = duration_ms)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(x = "Popularity", y = "Duration (ms)") +
  ggtitle("Distribution of Duration by Popularity")

#9. Group the data frame songs by track_artist and find the correspond median, Q3 - Q1 for danceability, energy, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence and counts for each track_artist. Save the result to unpopular_artists and sort the data frame via the descending order of counts. Print the top 10 unpopular artists and the corresponding information in unpopular_artists. Summarize your finding based on the result shown here

When looking at the data artist such as Alei Islah and Blackjesus Yoshua who were rated higher on the unpopular list and had higher median_danceability where they were around 0.7. with artists like these in comparison to ohters they also were higher in other areas such as median_energy and IQR_energy. This could give insight to a ptoential relationship and give more areas of research to obtain more information.

unpopular_artists <- songs %>%
  group_by(track_artist) %>%
  summarize(
    median_danceability = median(danceability),
    IQR_danceability = quantile(danceability, 0.75) - quantile(danceability, 0.25),
    median_energy = median(energy),
    IQR_energy = quantile(energy, 0.75) - quantile(energy, 0.25),
    median_speechiness = median(speechiness),
    IQR_speechiness = quantile(speechiness, 0.75) - quantile(speechiness, 0.25),
    median_acousticness = median(acousticness),
    IQR_acousticness = quantile(acousticness, 0.75) - quantile(acousticness, 0.25),
    median_instrumentalness = median(instrumentalness),
    IQR_instrumentalness = quantile(instrumentalness, 0.75) - quantile(instrumentalness, 0.25),
    median_liveness = median(liveness),
    IQR_liveness = quantile(liveness, 0.75) - quantile(liveness, 0.25),
    median_valence = median(valence),
    IQR_valence = quantile(valence, 0.75) - quantile(valence, 0.25),
    counts = n()
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(counts))
top_10_unpopular_artists <- head(unpopular_artists, 10)
print(top_10_unpopular_artists)

#10. Create two new variables: instrumentalness_status and boringness in the data frame songs. The variable instrumentalness_status has the value “High” for the songs that their instrumentalness is higher than the mean instrumentalness, otherwise it is “Low”. The variable boringness is calculated byboringness = loudness + tempo + (energy100) + (danceability100) Hint: You can use this command ifelse(condition, value1, value2), it assigns value 1 to the new variable when the condition is TRUE, otherwise it assign value 2 to the variable.

mean_instrumentalness <- mean(songs$instrumentalness)
songs <- songs %>%
  mutate(
    instrumentalness_status = ifelse(instrumentalness > mean_instrumentalness, "High", "Low")
  )
songs <- songs %>%
  mutate(
    boringness = loudness + tempo + (energy * 100) + (danceability * 100)
  )

#11. Create a bar plot that shows the conditional distribution of instrumentalness_status by the popularity of songs. Comment on your barplot.

When looking at the boxplot one can see the data is skewed left, as higher y values are found the more we move left on the x axis. Along with this the number of high instrumental_status is less than the amount of lower instrumental_status.

ggplot(songs, aes(x = popularity, fill = instrumentalness_status)) +
  geom_bar(position = "stack") +
  labs(x = "Popularity", y = "Count") +
  ggtitle("Conditional Distribution of Instrumentalness Status by Popularity")
